    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-26T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-26T21:00:00-05:00" n="732"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d732">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.543/277: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-27T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >April 27, 1944—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received April 27—6:17 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>736. Reference my 640, April 12, 11 a.m., regarding reregistration of trademarks.
                    I mentioned this matter April 25 to Foreign Minister<note n="7" xml:id="d732fn7"
                        >T. V. Soong.</note> and Political Vice Minister<note n="8" xml:id="d732fn8"
                        >K. C. Wu.</note> who inquired what is being done in other countries where
                    reregistration may not be readily possible due to war time conditions. If
                    information on this point is forthcoming from Department, I believe we may be
                    able to do something here to alleviate the situation.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
